meta.content: The supraoccipital is an endochondral bone that is located at the dorsal part of the occipital region of the cranium or the dorso-posterior part of the skull (TAO:0000595). The supraoccipital is an unpaired median bone and often develops a median process off its posteriormost end, and the process appears to contain dermal or membrane bone (e.g. Harrington, 1955). The supraoccipital of Siluriformes is often referred to as the parietal-supraoccipital or parieto-supraoccipital based on the hypothesis that it is a compound element resulting from fusion of the paired dermal parietal bones and the median endochondral supraoccipital (refs. Arratia; Uberon). However, we are not aware of definitive embryological or anatomical landmark evidence demonstrating and ongoing ontogenetic or prior phylogenetic fusion of those ossification centers. Accordingly, we use the term supraoccipital.

Plesiomorphically the caudal skeleton of catfishes is composed of a compound preural plus ural centrum, reduced second ural centrum, and associated median parhypural, six hypurals numbered counterclockwise from from hypural 1 adjacent to the parhypural, one uroneural, one epural. These components can be separate or fused in different ways.
The parhypural is the ventralmost fin-ray supporting element. It has a basal hemal arch, is carried on the compound preural plus ural centrum, and is anteriorly adjacent to hypural 1.
Hypural 6 is the dorsalmost hypural, located between the uroneural and hypural 5
The hypurals 3, 4, and 5 are in the dorsal part of the caudal skeleton, and these three components may be fused or separate.
Hypurals 1 and 2 are in the ventral part of the caudal skeleton posterior to the parhypural, and these two elements may be fused without the parhypural or other hypurals, or separate.
The hypurapophyses are lateral shelves or processes, with a spine-like or crest-like form, on the lateral wall of the hemal arch of the parhypural and on hypural 2.

char.label: Size of anterior dentations of the pectoral-fin spine

meta.content: Posterior dentations are commonly present along the posterior edge of the shaft.

Posterior dentations are paired, at least early in development, thus reflecting their origin from the halves of the first fin ray, i.e., they are derived from posterior expansions of the paired fin-spine segments. During development posterior-dentation halves may slip out of alignment with one another so that their paired nature is obscured.
